{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Sdg9pcR2MkrrtCYmWd74P8","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Story 9.2: Custom Workflow Creation\n2\t\n3\tStatus: backlog\n4\t\n5\t<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n6\t\n7\t## Story\n8\t\n9\tAs a developer,\n10\tI want to create a custom workflow YAML in my project and run it via `codeharness run --workflow my-workflow`,\n11\tso that I can define non-standard execution flows without patching the embedded default.\n12\t\n13\t## Acceptance Criteria\n14\t\n15\t1. **Given** a custom workflow file at `.codeharness/workflows/my-workflow.yaml` with valid `tasks` and `flow` sections\n16\t   **When** `codeharness run --workflow my-workflow` executes\n17\t   **Then** the custom workflow is loaded from `.codeharness/workflows/my-workflow.yaml`, validated against the workflow JSON schema, and used as the workflow for execution\n18\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n19\t\n20\t2. **Given** a custom workflow file at `.codeharness/workflows/my-workflow.yaml`\n21\t   **When** the file fails JSON schema validation (e.g., missing `tasks` key, unknown properties, invalid task fields)\n22\t   **Then** a `WorkflowParseError` is thrown with specific schema validation errors and the file path\n23\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n24\t\n25\t3. **Given** a custom workflow file that passes schema validation but has dangling task references in `flow` (e.g., `flow: [nonexistent]` where `nonexistent` is not defined in `tasks`)\n26\t   **When** the workflow resolver loads and validates it\n27\t   **Then** a `WorkflowParseError` is thrown with referential integrity errors listing the dangling references\n28\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n29\t\n30\t4. **Given** agent references in a custom workflow (e.g., `agent: my-custom-agent`)\n31\t   **When** the workflow is resolved and agents are compiled\n32\t   **Then** agent references resolve through the same embedded -> user -> project config chain as the default workflow\n33\t   **And** unknown agent names cause an error at agent resolution time (not at workflow parse time)\n34\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n35\t\n36\t5. **Given** the `codeharness run` command\n37\t   **When** invoked with `--workflow my-workflow`\n38\t   **Then** `resolveWorkflow()` is called with `{ cwd: projectDir, name: 'my-workflow' }` instead of the default name\n39\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n40\t\n41\t6. **Given** `--workflow my-workflow` is specified but no file exists at `.codeharness/workflows/my-workflow.yaml` and no embedded template exists for that name\n42\t   **When** `codeharness run --workflow my-workflow` executes\n43\t   **Then** the command exits with a clear error message indicating the workflow was not found\n44\t   **And** the error message includes the expected file path\n45\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n46\t\n47\t7. **Given** `codeharness run` is invoked without `--workflow`\n48\t   **When** the command executes\n49\t   **Then** the default workflow resolution chain (embedded -> user patch -> project patch) is used unchanged (backward-compatible)\n50\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n51\t\n52\t8. **Given** a custom workflow at `.codeharness/workflows/ci.yaml` alongside a patch at `.codeharness/workflows/ci.patch.yaml`\n53\t   **When** the workflow resolver loads `ci`\n54\t   **Then** the custom workflow is loaded directly (not patched) because it has no `extends` key — the patch file is ignored for full custom workflows\n55\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n56\t\n57\t9. **Given** `npm run build` is executed\n58\t   **When** the build completes\n59\t   **Then** it succeeds with zero errors\n60\t   **And** `npm run test:unit` passes with no regressions in existing test suites\n61\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n62\t\n63\t10. **Given** unit tests for custom workflow creation\n64\t    **When** `npm run test:unit` is executed\n65\t    **Then** tests cover: custom workflow loading by name, schema validation of custom workflows, referential integrity of custom workflows, `--workflow` CLI flag plumbing, missing workflow error path, backward-compatible default behavior, agent resolution with custom agent names\n66\t    <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n67\t\n68\t## Tasks / Subtasks\n69\t\n70\t- [ ] Task 1: Add `--workflow` CLI option to `src/commands/run.ts` (AC: #5, #6, #7)\n71\t  - [ ] Add `.option('--workflow <name>', 'Workflow name to load (default: \"default\")')` to the run command definition\n72\t  - [ ] Pass `options.workflow ?? 'default'` as the `name` parameter to `resolveWorkflow({ cwd: projectDir, name: workflowName })`\n73\t  - [ ] Keep the fallback logic for backward compatibility — if `resolveWorkflow` fails and name is `'default'`, try direct file parse\n74\t\n75\t- [ ] Task 2: Verify `resolveWorkflow()` already handles custom workflows by name (AC: #1, #2, #3, #8)\n76\t  - [ ] Confirm `resolveWorkflow({ name: 'my-workflow' })` loads `.codeharness/workflows/my-workflow.yaml` as a full custom workflow when no `extends` key is present (this path already exists at lines 312-319 of `workflow-parser.ts`)\n77\t  - [ ] Confirm that if no custom file exists and no embedded template exists for that name, `resolveWorkflow` throws `WorkflowParseError` with \"Embedded workflow not found\" (this is the existing error at line 329)\n78\t  - [ ] Confirm schema validation and referential integrity checks run on custom workflows (they go through `parseWorkflow` which calls `validateAndResolve`)\n79\t  - [ ] If any of the above behaviors are missing or broken, fix them\n80\t\n81\t- [ ] Task 3: Verify agent resolution works for custom agent names (AC: #4)\n82\t  - [ ] Confirm `run.ts` resolves agent names from the workflow's `tasks` through `resolveAgent()` / `compileSubagentDefinition()` — no changes expected since this is already name-based\n83\t  - [ ] Write a test confirming custom agent names in a custom workflow are passed to the agent resolver\n84\t\n85\t- [ ] Task 4: Write unit tests (AC: #9, #10)\n86\t  - [ ] Test: `resolveWorkflow({ name: 'my-workflow' })` loads a custom workflow from `.codeharness/workflows/my-workflow.yaml` in the project dir\n87\t  - [ ] Test: custom workflow fails schema validation — throws `WorkflowParseError` with errors\n88\t  - [ ] Test: custom workflow passes schema but has dangling flow refs — throws `WorkflowParseError`\n89\t  - [ ] Test: `resolveWorkflow({ name: 'nonexistent' })` with no matching file throws clear error\n90\t  - [ ] Test: `resolveWorkflow()` (no name) defaults to `'default'` — backward-compatible\n91\t  - [ ] Test: custom workflow with `extends` key is NOT treated as a full custom workflow (falls through to patch resolution)\n92\t  - [ ] Test: `--workflow` option is plumbed correctly in `run.ts` (mock-based test)\n93\t  - [ ] Test: existing `run.ts` tests still pass (no regressions)\n94\t\n95\t- [ ] Task 5: Build and test verification (AC: #9)\n96\t  - [ ] Run `npm run build` — zero errors\n97\t  - [ ] Run `npm run test:unit` — no regressions\n98\t\n99\t## Dev Notes\n100\t\n101\t### Architecture Context\n102\t\n103\tPer architecture-v2.md (AD1), `workflow-parser` covers FR13-15: workflow config patching and resolution. FR13 specifically states \"User can create custom workflows at project level or user level.\" Story 9-1 implemented the patch resolution chain (FR14, FR15). This story completes FR13 by exposing the custom workflow path through the CLI.\n104\t\n105\t### What Already Exists\n106\t\n107\tThe `resolveWorkflow()` function in `workflow-parser.ts` (lines 305-360) already supports:\n108\t- A `name` parameter defaulting to `'default'`\n109\t- Detection of full custom workflows at `.codeharness/workflows/{name}.yaml` (lines 312-319)\n110\t- Falls back to embedded template when no custom file exists (lines 322-342)\n111\t- Schema validation and referential integrity on all paths\n112\t\n113\tThe main gap is the **CLI plumbing**: `run.ts` calls `resolveWorkflow({ cwd: projectDir })` without passing a name, and there's no `--workflow` flag to specify one.\n114\t\n115\t### Changes Required\n116\t\n117\tThis is a small story. The primary changes are:\n118\t\n119\t1. **`src/commands/run.ts`** — Add `--workflow <name>` option (~3-5 lines changed)\n120\t2. **`src/commands/__tests__/run.test.ts`** — Add test for `--workflow` flag plumbing (~20-30 lines)\n121\t3. **`src/lib/__tests__/workflow-parser.test.ts`** — Add tests for custom workflow loading by name (~60-80 lines)\n122\t\n123\tNo changes to `workflow-parser.ts` are expected unless verification reveals a bug in the existing custom workflow path.\n124\t\n125\t### CLI Interface\n126\t\n127\t```\n128\tcodeharness run --workflow my-workflow\n129\tcodeharness run --workflow ci\n130\tcodeharness run                         # defaults to \"default\"\n131\t```\n132\t\n133\tThe `--workflow` value is a name, not a file path. It maps to:\n134\t- Custom: `.codeharness/workflows/{name}.yaml`\n135\t- Embedded: `templates/workflows/{name}.yaml`\n136\t- Patch: `.codeharness/workflows/{name}.patch.yaml` (only for embedded-based workflows)\n137\t\n138\t### Agent Resolution\n139\t\n140\tAgent names in custom workflows resolve through the same `resolveAgent()` chain. The workflow parser validates that task names referenced in `flow` exist in `tasks`, but does NOT validate that agent names resolve to real agents — that happens downstream in `run.ts` when `resolveAgent()` / `compileSubagentDefinition()` are called for each task's agent. This is the correct separation of concerns.\n141\t\n142\t### Edge Cases\n143\t\n144\t- Custom workflow with `extends` key: treated as a patch, not a full custom workflow. The resolver checks for `extends` at line 316.\n145\t- User-level custom workflow at `~/.codeharness/workflows/my-workflow.yaml`: NOT currently supported (only project-level). The `resolveWorkflow` function only checks `projectCustomPath`. This is acceptable — user-level is for patches, project-level is for full custom workflows.\n146\t- Multiple custom workflows: each has its own name, so `--workflow ci` and `--workflow deploy` load different files.\n147\t\n148\t### File Structure\n149\t\n150\t```\n151\tsrc/\n152\t  commands/\n153\t    run.ts                              (MODIFIED — add --workflow option)\n154\t    __tests__/\n155\t      run.test.ts                       (MODIFIED — add --workflow plumbing test)\n156\t  lib/\n157\t    workflow-parser.ts                  (LIKELY UNCHANGED — already supports name param)\n158\t    __tests__/\n159\t      workflow-parser.test.ts           (MODIFIED — add custom workflow name tests)\n160\t```\n161\t\n162\t### Dependencies\n163\t\n164\t- **Modified file:** `src/commands/run.ts` — ~5 line change (add option, pass name)\n165\t- **Modified file:** `src/commands/__tests__/run.test.ts` — ~30 lines new tests\n166\t- **Modified file:** `src/lib/__tests__/workflow-parser.test.ts` — ~80 lines new tests\n167\t- **No new files**\n168\t- **No new npm dependencies**\n169\t\n170\t### Anti-Patterns to Avoid\n171\t\n172\t- **Do NOT accept file paths** in `--workflow` — it takes a name, not a path. The resolver maps names to paths.\n173\t- **Do NOT create a `workflow-resolver.ts`** — resolution logic lives in `workflow-parser.ts` per architecture.\n174\t- **Do NOT validate agent names in the workflow parser** — agent resolution is a separate concern handled by `agent-resolver.ts`.\n175\t- **Do NOT modify `workflow.schema.json`** — the schema is correct as-is.\n176\t- **Do NOT break the default behavior** — omitting `--workflow` must work exactly as before.\n177\t\n178\t### Previous Story Intelligence\n179\t\n180\tFrom story 9-1 (workflow patch resolution):\n181\t- `resolveWorkflow()` was added with full patch chain support\n182\t- `deepMerge`, `loadWorkflowPatch`, `mergeWorkflowPatch` are tested and working\n183\t- Custom workflow detection (no `extends` key) was added as part of the resolver\n184\t- The `name` parameter already exists but is untested for non-default values\n185\t\n186\t### Git Intelligence\n187\t\n188\tRecent commits follow: `feat: story {key} — {description}`. This story modifies existing files only. The codebase uses TypeScript with ESM `.js` extensions in import paths. Tests use vitest with temp directory patterns.\n189\t\n190\t### References\n191\t\n192\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-v2.md#Story 9.2: Custom Workflow Creation]\n193\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-v2.md#FR13: User can create custom workflows at project level or user level]\n194\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-v2.md#AD1: Module Boundaries — workflow-parser covers FR13-15]\n195\t- [Source: src/lib/workflow-parser.ts — resolveWorkflow() lines 305-360, already supports name param]\n196\t- [Source: src/commands/run.ts — registerRunCommand, line 106 — current resolveWorkflow call without name]\n197\t- [Source: src/schemas/workflow.schema.json — workflow schema]\n198\t- [Source: templates/workflows/default.yaml — embedded default workflow]\n199\t- [Source: _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/9-1-workflow-patch-resolution.md — predecessor story]\n200\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01WtcmrZN9PZF2UTi7D5rt35","session_id":"c2800ecc-75a3-43b2-b3d8-396855aa3c3c","uuid":"e7558ff3-3e49-46a0-bad3-74f7fb669bb6","timestamp":"2026-04-03T03:07:55.520Z"}
